<DOC><DOCNO> AP880606-0187 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 2153EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Religion     06-06 0371</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Soviet-Religion,0382</SECOND><HEAD>Government Praises Church at Christian Millennium Conference</HEAD><BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>ZAGORSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government praised the RussianOrthodox Church on Monday in a message to religious leaders who methere to mark 1,000 years of Christianity in what is now the SovietUnion.   Official Radio Moscow said the message ``describes theintroduction of Christianity as a major event in the nation'shistory and in the development of Russia's statehood and culture.''   In Moscow, meanwhile, more than 50 religious dissidents crowdedinto an apartment for an alternate service to emphasize restrictionsthe government and church place on their religious lives.   The four-day Local Council conference in Zagorsk, a medievalcenter 40 miles northeast of Moscow that includes a monastery andseminary, will name nine new saints and consider internal churchbusiness, church officials said.   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual head of theChurch of England, representatives of the Roman Catholic Church, anddozens of officials from Eastern and Western churches enteredTrinity-St. Sergius accompanied by the pealing of bells.   Hundreds of Soviet citizens crowded around iron fences under ahot morning sun to watch the procession.   Journalists were not allowed into the conference. According toRadio Moscow, the government's message said ``The unity of people,irrespective of their attitude to religion, is essential to furtherprogress toward a society of social justice.''   It urged the church to continue working for peace and ``fosterthe humanitarian and moral potential of the nation,'' Radio Moscowsaid.   Included among the saints to be canonized are Russia's mostfamous icon painter, Andrei Rublev, and Dmitri Donskoy, a 14thcentury nobleman who defeated the Tatars in two major battles.   Church documents said the conference also would consider anadministrative charter for the church and discuss its activities onbehalf of world peace.   At the apartment in south Moscow, seven Russian Orthodox priestsbarred from serving in parishes conducted a service for people whocame from many areas of the Soviet Union, dissident AlexanderOgorodnikov said.   He said the purpose was to demonstrate that the priests ``arepart of the life of the church despite the view of authorities.''   Pentecostalists and Baptists also attended the service, he said.</TEXT></DOC>